=09=09=09=09Qantas, Australia=01,s leading airline, is to spend $4.6 billio=
n on 31 new=20
aircraft over the next ten years, including 12 new A3XX =01&superjumbos=018=
 from=20
Airbus. This gives the European consortium enough orders for a formal launc=
h=20
of its new aricraft. Though this is a significant victory for Airbus over=
=20
Boeing, Qantas will also buy six long-range 747s. Boeing said that sales of=
=20
its smaller 777 will exceed $18 billion this year, well ahead of similar=20
Airbus planes.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Creditors of Daewoo Motor, an insolvent South Korean car maker,=
 agreed to=20
provide further loans of 728 billion won ($605m), after the unions had=20
accepted a restructuring that would include job cuts and sales of assets.=
=20
This may help to persuade General Motors and Fiat to buy Daewoo.
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Glaxo Wellcome, a British drug company, withdrew Lotronex, its=
=20
irritable-bowel syndrome treatment, from the American market because of=20
worries by the Food and Drug Administration over its side-effects. It is=20
unlikely that the drug will now be launched in other countries, and it may =
be=20
withdrawn elsewhere.=20
=09=09=09=09
=09=09=09=09Weyerhaeuser, an American forest-products company, made a $5.4 =
billion=20
hostile bid for a rival, Willamette Industries after the latter rejected an=
=20
unsolicited offer. Weyerhaeuser did not increase its price, although it may=
=20
yet be forced to go higher to beat out rivals.=20
